{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496516"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:49:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1376"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1376"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.82,0.03,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47077"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1376"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"431"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12293"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47077"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with concerns about his right eye. He has noted a slow deterioration of vision over decades with intermittent exacerbation of discomfort, particularly in summer. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.  He is retired and has always been an active surfer and cyclist.  On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Ocular examination reveals the findings shown in the image.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Episcleritis","Pterygium","Scleritis","Pinguecula","Trachoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a very large \u003Cstrong\u003Epterygium\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a triangular fibrovascular subepithelial ingrowth of degenerative bulbar conjunctival tissue over the limbus onto the cornea.  It must be causing considerable distortion of his vision due to astigmatism (irregular curvature of the cornea) - the vast majority of focusing is done by the cornea and only a little by the lens.  Risk factors include chronic UV light exposure, dry climates, and wind. It is sometimes referred to as \u0022surfer\u0027s eye\u0022. It is common in Australia, and presents more with men in their 20 - 40s. Wearing quality sunglasses and using a wide-brimmed hat help to prevent the development of pterygium. Pterygia are often asymptomatic but can cause irritation, redness, foreign body sensation, and blurred vision if they extend over the visual axis. Treatment includes lubrication, steroid drops, and surgical excision for severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the episcleral tissue between the conjunctiva and sclera. It presents with sectoral redness, irritation and watery discharge. The vessels blanch with phenylephrine and the sclera itself appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a more serious painful inflammatory condition involving the deeper sclera itself. The sclera appears blue-red and does not blanch with phenylephrine. It can be associated with collagen vascular diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epinguecula\u003C/strong\u003E is a yellowish elevated conjunctival nodule near the limbus. It is a degenerative lesion related to chronic UV exposure and aging. Unlike a pterygium, it does not grow onto the cornea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrachoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic keratoconjunctivitis caused by Chlamydia trachomatis. It causes follicular hypertrophy, conjunctival scarring, and corneal vascularization and opacity. It is a major cause of preventable blindness in developing countries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Risk factors for pterygium include prolonged periods of exposure to bright sunlight and wind","Pterygium is also known as \u0022surfer\u0027s eye\u0022"],"references":["Contributors for Vision Eye Institute, 2020. Ptergium. Access at: https://visioneyeinstitute.com.au/services/pterygium/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1376"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18410"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18410"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0a6ede82-dd86-4308-8fb9-cff43f12e406.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0a6ede82-dd86-4308-8fb9-cff43f12e406.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":567,"height":387}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-15T23:23:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-15T23:23:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1376"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47077"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"